@dathoratiospams but why talk about only the most trivial issues compared with the clearly more pressing and consequential ones going on in other parts of the world? I’m frustrated because I can’t count the number of discussions I’ve heard about the wage gap, privilege, micro-agressions, pronouns, and gender when there are so many instances of genocide and inhumane treatment of people that go unnoticed and untalked about.

@no._.name1248 that’s a fair point, and there does need to be more global activists, but blaming that on gender activists is like is someone got upset with women for trying to get the right to vote when Civil Rights were a more pressing and important issue. If we focus on all the big things, all the little things will never be changed, and some of those little things are underlying contributors to bigger ones. Basically what I’m saying is that you shouldn’t get mad at other activists for being “the wrong type of activist”, you should get mad at the self-proclaimed global activists that aren’t talking about these issues. You don’t blame the State Farm employee for a lack of employees at Progressive. Or maybe get upset with the countless people (myself included) who don’t have global activist accounts that totally could. I do understand your emotions and feel them too, though. This is not getting as much attention as it should.
